  "ATP and Cellular Energy": "",
  "This lesson covers the fundamental measures of center used to analyze and summarize data sets. You'll learn how to calculate and apply the mean, median, and mode, and understand when each is most appropriate.": "",
  "What is the surface area-to-volume ratio, and why does it limit cell size?": "",
  "Surface area-to-volume ratio and cell size: (1) Mathematical basis: for a sphere, SA = 4πr², V = (4/3)πr³. As r doubles: SA increases 4×, V increases 8× → SA:V ratio halves. For a cube: side length s → SA = 6s², V = s³ → SA:V = 6/s. (2) Biological implications: all exchange between cell and environment (nutrients in, waste out, O₂/CO₂ exchange) occurs across the plasma membrane (surface area). All metabolic activity produces waste and consumes nutrients proportional to volume. When volume grows faster than surface area, the membrane cannot service the cell's metabolic needs → diffusion distances become too great. (3) Solutions organisms use: remain small (bacteria ~1-10 μm, typical animal cell ~10-30 μm). Folded membranes increase effective surface area (microvilli in intestinal cells increase absorptive surface ~20×, mitochondrial cristae). Flattened or elongated shapes (red blood cells are biconcave discs). Multinucleate cells (skeletal muscle fibers). (4) Exceptions: ostrich egg (~15 cm) but metabolically inactive yolk; neurons are long but thin; Caulerpa (giant single-celled alga) uses cytoplasmic streaming.": "",
  "A pathologist examines a tumor biopsy using both light microscopy and TEM, observing cells with enlarged nuclei, abnormal chromatin patterns, increased mitotic figures, and disorganized ultrastructure. Rudolf Virchow, who founded cellular pathology, proposed that disease arises from abnormal cells. How does this case illustrate Virchow's cellular pathology and its connection to cell theory?": "",
  "Virchow's cellular pathology and cancer: (1) Virchow's 'Die Cellularpathologie' (1858): groundbreaking work proposing that all diseases involve changes in normal cells. Replaced the humoral theory (disease from imbalances in blood, phlegm, yellow bile, black bile) and miasma theory (disease from bad air). Key principle: every pathological condition can be traced to abnormal cellular activity. (2) Cancer connection: Virchow recognized cancer as uncontrolled cell proliferation — tumor cells are derived from normal cells (tenet 3: cells from cells) that have undergone transformation. Modern understanding: cancer results from accumulated mutations in oncogenes (gain-of-function) and tumor suppressors (loss-of-function). (3) Microscopic observations in the biopsy: Enlarged nuclei → genomic instability, aneuploidy. Abnormal chromatin → epigenetic dysregulation, aberrant gene expression. Increased mitotic figures → loss of cell cycle checkpoint control (p53, Rb mutations). Disorganized ultrastructure (TEM) → disrupted organelle organization, abnormal membrane structures. (4) Modern pathology: histopathology (light microscopy of tissue sections) remains the gold standard for cancer diagnosis. EM used for specific tumor classification. Immunohistochemistry and molecular markers complement microscopy. All built on Virchow's foundational insight that disease is cellular.": ""
